# Ontario… Why Not Us?

---

I'm going to admit something embarrassing: until last week, I had never heard of Greg Brockman.

I know. For a guy who runs an AI consulting firm, that's a bit of an "Emperor has no clothes" moment. But honestly, I think a lot of people who talk about AI a lot are in the same boat — we know the name Sam Altman, we've got opinions about OpenAI (chat gpt), and most of us have probably scrolled past enough posts chirping its leader to feel like we understand the full picture.

We don't.

I stayed up way too late listening to the Rick Rubin podcast — Tetragrammaton — and Greg Brockman, co-founder and president of OpenAI, was the guest. Nearly three hours total. And I walked away from it feeling like I'd had my mental model of the whole AI industry quietly reset.

> 📺 [**[Watch/listen here — Tetragrammaton with Rick Rubin: Greg Brockman Part 1]** ](https://youtu.be/mI30_ueZ7CU?si=Xx0krwfzqqMZTTRT)

---

## What Rick Rubin Does That Nobody Else Does

Rick Rubin is not a tech journalist. He's not trying to catch anyone in a contradiction or get a clip. He's just… curious. And that quality — genuine curiosity, zero ego — pulls something out of his guests that you just don't see anywhere else. Plus he doesn't give a shit if he gets views. Look at who he has had on and the small number of views on each episode, its almost like he does not want people to find this.

Anyways… Brockman talks about how AI actually works. About the early days of OpenAI. About his personal relationship with Elon Musk. About what they actually believed they were building and why. You come away understanding the company not as a monolith or a PR machine, but as a group of people who were genuinely trying to do something nobody had done before and making it up as they went.

The "easy to hate on" version of OpenAI and Sam Altman doesn't survive this podcast. That doesn't mean all the criticism is wrong — but the full picture is a lot more interesting.

---

## The Thing That Should Make Every Ontario Business Owner Uncomfortable

Here's the part that really got under my skin.

Brockman talks about the foundational research that made all of this possible. And if you know anything about that history, you know where it lives: Toronto. Specifically, the University of Toronto, where Geoffrey Hinton — the Nobel Prize-winning "Godfather of AI" — spent decades building the research that the entire modern AI industry is built on. His work on neural networks, done largely in Canada with Canadian funding, is what made ChatGPT, Gemini, and every other tool you've heard of possible.

We didn't just contribute to AI. We literally invented the foundations of it.

And yet, according to Statistics Canada, only 12.2% of Canadian businesses are currently using AI in their core operations. Two-thirds have no plans to adopt it at all.

That's not a gap. That's a chasm. And its embarrassing. We have the resources, the minds and the companies to become a world leader in AI. We should be experiencing a higher ROI from AI than any other region in the world. We should be using AI to create the change we want to see in the world. Instead, we are watching as the world (USA and China) passes us by and creates the rules. I started this company because I refuse to let that happen. Fuck that! We were the pioneers of this, and we still are.

---

## Required Reading (and Listening)

Sorry about the tangent, I am just fired up and you should be too. If the Brockman podcast gets you interested, the next stop is *The Scaling Era: An Oral History of AI, 2019–2025* by Dwarkesh Patel and Gavin Leech — published by Stripe Press. It's exactly what it sounds like: a primary-source, oral history format covering the most consequential five years in the history of the technology. The people who built it, in their own words, telling you how it actually happened.

> 📖 [The Scaling Era: An Oral History of AI, 2019–2025](https://a.co/d/0dzubKsr)

It's probably the best single document for understanding why AI is moving the way it is and why the pace isn't slowing down. Required reading, as far as I'm concerned.

---

## So What Do You Do With This?

You don't have to go down the rabbit hole the way I do. You don't have to read the books or listen to three hours of podcast to make AI useful for your business today.

But here's what I'd push back on: the idea that this is still optional. That you can keep watching from the sidelines while you figure out if it's real. It's real. The businesses in London and Windsor that are getting ahead of this right now are not doing anything complicated — they're just starting.

If you want to understand what "starting" actually looks like for your specific business, that's exactly what we do at Avant. No jargon, no grand transformation promises — just practical steps that make sense for where you are today.

